![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/323878/54722821-cbb32f80-4b22-11e9-9626-ec35fd4702c3.png)

Have an extension with  

```ts
    let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('extension.helloWorld', () => {
        vscode.window.showInputBox(<vscode.InputBoxOptions>{ prompt: 'test' });
    });
```

click the prompt of the quickinput, and it gets a weird focus ring which we suppress other places.

I would like to have a way for extensions to resolve strings containing variables like `${workspaceFolder}`, similarly to how this is done for tasks and other configuration.

I am trying to write an extension that hooks into a script which may be named differently in different projects. I will search for the script in a default location, but I've added a setting to allow a workspace to override the location as needed.

My code looks something like this:

```json
// package.json
...
"contributes": {
  "configuration": {
    "type": "object",
    "title": "My Extension",
    "properties": {
      "myext.entryPoint": {
        "type": "string",
        "default": ""
      }
    }
  }
```

```ts
import * as vscode from 'vscode';
import * as path from 'path';

function getEntryPoint() {
    const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('myext');
    const entryPoint = config.get<string>('entryPoint');

    if (entryPoint) {
        return entryPoint;
    } else {
        // If the setting doesn't override the entry point, 
        // assume it is in the workspace folder with a default name.
        return path.join(vscode.workspace.rootPath, 'the_script.py');
    }
}
```

If I then create a workspace with these settings...

```json
// .vscode/settings.json
{
  "myext.entryPoint": "${workspaceFolder}/a_different_script.py"
}
```

...I see that `config.get('entryPoint')` returns exactly that string without resolving `${workspaceFolder}`, so I need to somehow resolve that variable. I have enough information to do a search and replace and resolve it on my own, but it would be much more convenient if I had some way to ask VS Code to resolve it, either by giving some form of access to [variableResolver.ts](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/workbench/services/configurationResolver/common/variableResolver.ts) or having WorkspaceConfiguration resolve the variables when I get them.
